04658nam a22005775i 9781501752605DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017526057 a10.1515/97815017526052doi  a(DE-B1597)576842  a(OCoLC)1141971526  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKZ6471b.M356 2020 7aLAW0510002bisacsh04a341.6/72231 aMantilla, Giovanni, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLawmaking under Pressure :bInternational Humanitarian Law and Internal Armed Conflict /cGiovanni Mantilla. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Failure in Paris, Success in Geneva -- t1. Social Pressure in International Lawmaking -- t2. Normative Gatekeeping (1863–1921) -- t3. Squaring the Circle -- t4. A Winding Road to the Additional Protocols (1950–1968) -- t5. A Revolution in Lawmaking? (1968–1977) -- tConclusion: Custom and Socially Pressured Codification -- tAppendix: Research Design -- tNotes -- tArchival Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Lawmaking under Pressure, Giovanni Mantilla analyzes the origins and development of the international humanitarian treaty rules that now exist to regulate internal armed conflict. Until well into the twentieth century, states allowed atrocious violence as an acceptable product of internal conflict. Why have states created international laws to control internal armed conflict? Why did states compromise their national security by accepting these international humanitarian constraints? Why did they create these rules at improbable moments, as European empires cracked, freedom fighters emerged, and fears of communist rebellion spread? Mantilla explores the global politics and diplomatic dynamics that led to the creation of such laws in 1949 and in the 1970s.By the 1949 Diplomatic Conference that revised the Geneva Conventions, most countries supported legislation committing states and rebels to humane principles of wartime behavior and to the avoidance of abhorrent atrocities, including torture and the murder of non-combatants. However, for decades, states had long refused to codify similar regulations concerning violence within their own borders. Diplomatic conferences in Geneva twice channeled humanitarian attitudes alongside Cold War and decolonization politics, even compelling reluctant European empires Britain and France to accept them. Lawmaking under Pressure documents the tense politics behind the making of humanitarian laws that have become touchstones of the contemporary international normative order.Mantilla not only explains the pressures that resulted in constraints on national sovereignty but also uncovers the fascinating international politics of shame, status, and hypocrisy that helped to produce the humanitarian rules now governing internal conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil war. 0aHumanitarian lawxHistory. 0aHumanitarian lawxSocial aspects. 0aSocial pressurexPolitical aspects. 4aHumanities & Human Rights. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  aNew histories of international law, the global south and international law, status politics, humanitarian law, internal conflict,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501752605?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501752605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501752605/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  C